  "event_preview": "Texas Motor Speedway is a 1.5-mile (2.414 km) quad-oval in Fort Worth, Texas, repaved and reconfigured in 2017 — Turns 1 and 2 were reduced from 24 to 20 degrees of banking while Turns 3 and 4 retained 24 degrees, creating an asymmetric character that produces distinct handling challenges at each end. The Würth 400 is the eleventh race of the 2026 NASCAR Cup Series season, run over 267 laps (400.5 miles) with stage breaks at laps 80 and 165. A new left-side tyre compound and a revised right-side construction — both introduced at intermediate ovals earlier in 2026 — will be used for the first time at Texas this weekend.\n\nJoey Logano is the defending winner, having taken victory in last year's race from seventh on the grid. Tyler Reddick leads the championship standings after winning five of the first nine races, though a quiet 14th-place result at Talladega — where Carson Hocevar claimed his first career Cup Series win — left Reddick without a dominant performance on the intermediate-style tracks for the first time in 2026. Hendrick Motorsports arrives as the all-time wins leader at Texas with 12 victories, also leading in poles (eight), top fives (46), top tens (81) and laps led (3,263). Kyle Busch leads all active drivers in wins at the track with four, while William Byron has the best average finish in the NextGen era at 6.0, including one win. The 38-car field includes open entries from Chad Finchum and Corey Heim, meaning all 36 full-time chartered cars make the race.\n\nThe all-time Cup Series qualifying record at Texas belongs to Kurt Busch, who posted a 200.951 mph lap on November 3, 2017 — the first time a stock car had exceeded 200 mph on a 1.5-mile oval in qualifying. The track race record belongs to Greg Biffle, who averaged 160.577 mph during the November 14, 2012 event.",
